<h2><span><span class="conr">#1</span> <a href="viewtopic.php?pid=173#p173">2017-02-18 17:14:24</a></span></h2>
<div class="box">
<div class="inbox">
<div class="postbody">
<div class="postleft">
<dl>
<dt><strong>Jay</strong></dt>
<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Guest</strong></dd>
</dl>
</div>
<div class="postright">
<h3>[SOLVED] Download Security</h3>
<div class="postmsg">
<p>Okay so I&#039;m trying to figure out where you signing key is but I see that neither your hashes or your ISO has been signed. I&#039;m sorry but this is completely unacceptable if you&#039;re going to call yourself a secure Linux operating system. No security conscious person in their right mind is going to download and use a distro when they can&#039;t even check it&#039;s integrity.</p><p>Not only this but the hashes you do offer, you have specifically chosen to not use your SSL/TLS certificate on the page where you&#039;ve made those hashes available. I mean, how do you really expect anyone to take your claims seriously if you can&#039;t even offer proper download security? I&#039;m sorry if this email upsets you but I just can&#039;t believe what I&#039;m seeing here. I considered checking the distribution out but not after this. I always thought of these kind of Linux distros as a shortcut anyway for script kiddies but at least Kali Linux get&#039;s their download security correct.</p><p>Even distros with no focus on security of any kind offer proper download security. Take Linux Mint for example. They learned their lesson and you will to and the hard way like they did if you don&#039;t change your methods.</p><p>You need to offer a properly secured page, possibly even a Tor Onion Service where the hashes, signatures, signing key as well as your ISOs can be downloaded from in a secure manner. You need to sign both your hashes and your ISO&#039;s and offer strong hashes such as sha512 and sha256. Then maybe I&#039;ll consider giving it a look but as this is right now I&#039;m extremely disappointed in what I see and couldn&#039;t recommend it to anyone. I&#039;d probably warn anyone who asks to stay away.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
