<h3>Re: [SOLVED] Download Security</h3>
<div class="postmsg">
<p><a href="https://postimg.org/image/btrns7e8t/" rel="nofollow"><span class="postimg"><img src="https://s22.postimg.org/btrns7e8t/IMG_20170218_175918.jpg" alt="IMG_20170218_175918.jpg"/></span></a></p><p><a href="https://postimg.org/image/s29xhb18r/" rel="nofollow"><span class="postimg"><img src="https://s9.postimg.org/s29xhb18r/IMG_20170218_175952.jpg" alt="IMG_20170218_175952.jpg"/></span></a></p><p>no signatures on our hashes? wre you serious? we offer several hashes for each image in a document which is digitally signed with 3 different gpg keys with detailed info on the used keys inside the signed document itself where one of the keys is mine and is certified by some debian developers (sullivan and paleino), and another one is used for our repository</p><p>the ssl/https question is an open issue for almost all the GNU/LINUX distributions because the mirror servers are hosted by third parties and https will not ensure you that th4 content is genuine anyway, the only solution is to use end to end signatures with gpg, so that you are 100% sure that what you have is what i have released</p><p>infact even the official debian mirrors (including the security one) are in http and they are secure not because of server-to-client encryption (which is useless in this case) but because of developer-to-client signatures which is way better</p><p>and just to let you know, most (if not every) kali-rolling apt and iso mirror servers are in http</p><br/><p>anyway if you check, all our services that are not related to our mirrors network, are ssl-enforced, while important things (ssl or not) are gpg-enfor ed with at least my key (with several signatures) and with the repository key (integrated in the system keyring)</p><br/><br/><p>anyway i am not here to defend the project &quot;against&quot; you</p><p>i just want to clarify where you are wromg and i&#039;ll try to improve how we offer this kind of security, for example even if i can&#039;t pur ssl encryption on our mirror servers, i can offer some things via ssl on a different server, for example the file with the signed hashes can be offered by our central server instead of one of the repositories as it is a very small file and a CDN os not strictly needed for it</p><br/><p>if you have other questions about our way of considering security, feel free to ask whatever you want<br/>for example an interesting topic no one asks is how we build our packages or if we recompile some critical debian sources or how we verify packages authenticity when importing stuff from debian or if this kind of things is automatic or if there is someone to manuallu check everything and who he/she is</p>
</div>
<div class="postsignature postmsg"><hr/><p>Lorenzo &quot;Palinuro&quot; Faletra - Parrot Security</p><p>GPG FINGERPRINT: B350 5059 3C2F 7656 40E6 DDDB 97CA A129 F4C6 B9A4<br/>GPG Info: <a href="https://pgp.mit.edu/pks/lookup?op=vindex&amp;search=0x97CAA129F4C6B9A4" rel="nofollow">http://pgp.mit.edu/pks/lookup?op=vindex … 29F4C6B9A4</a><br/>GPG Key: <a href="https://pgp.mit.edu/pks/lookup?op=get&amp;search=0x97CAA129F4C6B9A4" rel="nofollow">http://pgp.mit.edu/pks/lookup?op=get&amp;se … 29F4C6B9A4</a></p></div>
